			<title>Final Fantasy Record Breaker - F2P Nostalgia</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?77756-Final-Fantasy-Record-Breaker-F2P-Nostalgia&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Thu, 02 Apr 2015 00:36:56 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[This game recently came to my attention and I decided to try it out. I didn't particularly like it myself, but I think there are aspects of it that might make it something you guys would want to know about, and thus the thread. 
 
Mobile gaming is a big thing right now, and with declining profits...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>This game recently came to my attention and I decided to try it out. I didn't particularly like it myself, but I think there are aspects of it that might make it something you guys would want to know about, and thus the thread.<br />
<br />
Mobile gaming is a big thing right now, and with declining profits in traditional spaces, a large number of Japanese developers have been resorting to experimenting with mobile games in order to survive, much to the dismay of traditional gamers yearning for new entries in their favorite IPs. I don't want to get too offtopic here, just to say that Square is no exception.<br />
<br />
Record Breaker is the newest entry in a series of such projects. It's a free to play game, and while supposedly not as egregious as most, it has many of the things you would expect from such a game. You have stamina that must be recharged over time before you can do more battles, you can buy chances for loot, etc.<br />
<br />
The format and story of the game is that you exist in a world that chronicles fictional adventures from other universes, and preserves them as paintings in a special magical museum. These paintings thus inspire peace in that world itself. The paintings begin to disappear, and it's your job to bring them back by &quot;reliving&quot; those moments.<br />
<br />
As you can probably guess, those fictional universes are all from numbered Final Fantasy games. The tutorial has you &quot;reliving&quot; the first Mako generator battle in FF7. What this really means, and why I keep putting it in quotations, is that you fight battles themed to that game and that plot. You don't replay the actual sequences themselves. When you are done you get a screenshot of the original game and some sort of text blurb referencing it.<br />
<br />
So it's classic 8-16 bit Final Fantasy ATB combat. Meters fill, then you can select commands. It's actually simplified a great deal (attack, defend, two magic spells, special) and in my opinion is a little brainless, but it serves a purpose which I will get to in a bit. Each painting tends to consist of a few rounds of battle, and sometimes a boss, all relevant to the game in question. <br />
<br />
For completing a painting, you are awarded points based on how well you did, and earn a variety of rewards, from weapons and armor, to new party members. Aside from the main character, party members are all from their respective Final Fantasy games, and you can set up your party composition however you want (although the game did inform me that using characters in their own specific worlds gives stat bonuses).<br />
<br />
<br />
So the reason why I am making a thread about this at all is for the nostalgia. The sprites and the music in particular are great for this reason. While if you want something meatier there are arguably better options, this provides an adaptation of ATB combat that doesn't have to be particularly time consuming.<br />
<br />
I am sure there are some of you that like old rpgs, but don't have the time to get into newer ones. This is essentially a classic Final Fantasy game that you can play in ten minute chunks. <br />
<br />
It's available both for ios and Android. I won't be playing any more of it myself, but if any of you do feel free to share your likes or dislikes.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
